              "items": [
                {
                  "id": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3np1x156/manifest/annotation/p3",
                  "type": "Annotation",
                  "motivation": "commenting",
                  "body": {
                    "type": "TextualBody",
                    "value": "<p>remind you, that selections from the writings of\n                                                  <persName>Maimonides</persName> were<lb/>\n                                        published by <persName>Bernard</persName>, though not those\n                                        which I have.<lb/> The book sold well among christians and\n                                        even among Jews<lb/> no doubt because the author was a\n                                                  chestiuvuad<add>?</add>.</p>\n                              <p rend=\"indent(1)\">You will ere this have received the first\n                                                  <sic>instalment</sic> of my<lb/> promised article\n                                        on the settlement of the Jews in\n                                                  <placeName>England</placeName>. It<lb/> is a dark\n                                        subject and perhaps you and your readers may say<lb/> a\n                                        profitable one, but it is one which I was compelled to\n                                        write<lb/> in my lecture on the Jews of\n                                                  <placeName>England</placeName> and you have it in\n                                                  <add>?</add><lb/> form. The Sermon or the\n                                                  <add>Hebrew</add> you will perceive is<lb/> one of\n                                        a series therefore if you have not already published<lb/> it\n                                        and will press it back a month or so, inducting the<lb/>\n                                        Enquiry “instead, I will send you one or two others on\n                                        the<lb/> same subject. With the 2<hi rend=\"sup\">nd</hi>\n                                        <sic>instalment</sic> of the “Enquiry” some<lb/> you\n                                                  <sic>you</sic> will have enough of my scribbles\n                                        has at least<lb/> 3 Occidents to come i.e. If you reckon the\n                                        Sermon and<lb/> publish the <sic><hi rend=\"underline\"\n                                                  >instalments</hi></sic> separately if you print\n                                        them<lb/> together pray let me know for I am quite in the\n                                        dark as to your<lb/> proceedings as we get the Occidents so\n                                        late here, but not<lb/> here only. Why should <persName>Mrs\n                                                  Joel</persName> of <placeName>London</placeName>\n                                        say she had not<lb/> received any for the last 3 months.\n                                        Prenez garde, Monsieur le<lb/> Redacteur! Thanks for the\n                                                  aptra<add>?</add> she sent me. I shall<lb/> (in\n                                        return/) expect the same favor every time any papers of<lb/>\n                                        mine may be inserted. I send you a report (or rather a<lb/>\n                                        digest of one since it would be inconvenient to send so\n                                        much<lb/> paper, of the first years operations of our\n                                        society. If you<lb/>\n                                        <sic>dont</sic> feel inclined to publish all the\n                                                  <add>?</add> names<lb/> it contains, pray do not,\n                                        but just say 'an those will that<lb/> “there follow the\n                                        names” The committees wanted to give the people enough<lb/>\n                                        but I think the feel stated should be quite sufficient. I am\n                                        quite pleased with <persName>Mrs Jacob<lb/>\n                                                  Joseph</persName>, lately arrived among us, and\n                                        indeed so<lb/> are all here. She is extremely amiable and\n                                        intelligent<lb/> I regret much that I have not been able to\n                                        see her<lb/> as often as I could wish. Preuis<add>?</add> le\n                                        temps viendra<lb/> Pray do not allow so long &amp; time to\n                                        intervene</p>"
                  },
                  "target": "https://colenda.library.upenn.edu/items/ark:/81431/p3np1x156/canvas/p3"
